                     <supportDesc>
                        <support>
                           <p>
                              <material>Limestone</material> 
                              <rs type="objectType">block</rs> in situ at Ghirza, Wadi Zemzem (map ref. W 7052), over the door of one of the mausolea in the group nearest the habitations.
               The mausoleum is that illustrated by De Mathuisieulx, <title level="j">Nouvelles Archives</title>, XII (1904) pi. IV, and by Bauer, <title level="j">Air. Ital.</title> VI (1935) 62, fig. 1. </p>
                        </support>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout>Inscribed within a panel (die, <dimensions>
                              <width unit="metre">0.47</width>
                              <height unit="metre">0.36</height>
                           </dimensions>) flanked by two <rs type="decoration">eagles</rs>.</layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote>The lettering of this inscription is very much better than that of the inscriptions on other mausolea at Ghirza, and strongly suggests that this is the earliest tomb in the group nearest the habitations: this accords with its position in relation to the other mausolea.</handNote>
                     <handNote> 
